{{for|the modern settlement|Dolichi}} [[File:Thessaly.jpg|thumb|350px|Map showing ancient Thessaly. Doliche is shown to the centre top near Mount Olympus.]] '''Doliche''' ({{lang-el|Δολίχη}})<ref>{{Cite Ptolemy|3.13.42}}</ref> was an ancient Greek city and [[polis]] (city-state) in [[Perrhaebia]] in [[Thessaly]], situated at the foot of [[Mount Olympus]].<ref name=Poleis>{{cite book|author= Mogens Herman Hansen & Thomas Heine Nielsen |title= An inventory of archaic and classical poleis|year= 2004|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]|location=New York|isbn= 0-19-814099-1|chapter= Thessaly and Adjacent Regions|pages= 722-723}}</ref> Doliche, with the two neighbouring towns of [[Azorus]] and [[Pythion]] (Pythium), formed a [[Tripolis (region of Thessaly)|Tripolis]].
During the [[Roman–Seleucid War]], the Tripolis was ravaged by an army of the [[Aetolian League]] in the year 191&nbsp;BCE.<ref>{{Cite Livy|36.10}}</ref> During the [[Third Macedonian War]] the three towns surrendered to the army of [[Perseus of Macedon]] in the year 171&nbsp;BCE,<ref>{{Cite Livy|42.53}}</ref> but that same year the [[ancient Rome|Romans]] reconquered the three.<ref>{{Cite Livy|42.67}}</ref> In the year 169&nbsp;BCE troops arrived from the Roman consul [[Quintus Marcius Philippus (consul 186 BC)|Quintus Marcius Philippus]] who camped between Azorus and Doliche.<ref>{{Cite Polybius|28.11, 28.13.1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Livy|44.2}}</ref>
The three cities minted a common coin with the inscription "ΤΡΙΠΟΛΙΤΑΝ".<ref>{{cite book|author= Mogens Herman Hansen & Thomas Heine Nielsen |title= An inventory of archaic and classical poleis|year= 2004|publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]|location=New York|isbn= 0-19-814099-1|chapter= Thessaly and Adjacent Regions|pages= 721-722}}</ref>
The site is occupied by the modern town of [[Dolichi]];<ref>{{Cite Barrington|50}}</ref><ref>{{Cite DARE|32099}}</ref> when [[William Martin Leake]] visited the site in the 19th century, he found two fragments of [[Doric order|Doric]] columns {{convert|2|ft|8|in|cm}} in diameter in a ruined church, and a sepulchral stone in the burying-ground, together with some squared blocks.<ref>[[William Martin Leake]], ''Northern Greece'', vol. iii. p. 344.</ref>
