[[File:FFM logo words black.png|thumb|logo of FFM (Fellowship of Faith for Muslims)]] '''Fellowship of Faith for the Muslims''' (FFM) is an international fellowship of [[Christians]] who have a concern for the [[Muslim world]].
== FFM origins == It was founded by Annie van Sommer, her niece, and John Martin Cleaver through the [[Keswick Convention]], England after a talk by [[Samuel Zwemer]] in 1915,<ref>International Journal of Frontier Missions, Vol.13:4 Oct-Dec 1996, p.166</ref> and since then has maintained its emphasis on praying for Muslims worldwide.<ref>Barnes, Paul: 'Taking Hold of God, the Story of a Prayer Movement', Kitab Interserve Resources, UK 2015, p.9</ref> To facilitate this [[prayer]], resources listing topics to pray for are mailed out around the world, to encourage more Christians to pray, in the hope that Muslims will be blessed and to come to know the saving knowledge of Jesus Christ, and to increase this interest and vision.
== FFM Today == The Fellowship is organised by [[committees]] of unpaid volunteers, some of whom are missionaries, but FFM itself is not a mission agency. FFM in the UK and in North America compiles and sends out prayer requests, sourced from various mission agencies, relating to the topic of Muslim-majority [[people groups]] across the world, [[Christians]] living among them, and opportunities they may have to share their faith, eg. [[Bible translation]], radio or TV programmes, and [[Christian Church|church]] activities. The members who receive the monthly bulletins (by post or email) pay a [[subscription]], and are invited to gather for FFM prayer meetings and [[conferences]]. FFM currently has [[branches]] in the UK <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ffm.org.uk/ministry.php|title=FFM - Christian Prayer for the Muslim World|website=www.ffm.org.uk|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>, and in North America <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ffmna.org/site/about.php?id=mission|title=FFM - Fellowship of Faith for Muslims - Mission & History|website=www.ffmna.org|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> (which publishes prayer items 3 times a year), and in New Zealand.
