{{nihongo|'''Tenri'''|天理市|Tenri-shi}} is a [[Cities of Japan|city]] located in [[Nara Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. The modern city was founded on April 1, 1954, and is named after the [[Japanese new religion]] [[Tenrikyo]], which has its [[Tenrikyo Church Headquarters|headquarters]] in the city.
As of April 1, 2015, the city has an estimate [[population]] of 66,866, and 29,169 households.<ref name="Nara150401">{{cite web | url=http://www.pref.nara.jp/secure/114166/jinkou27-4.xls | title=市町村別推計人口・世帯数 | work=[[Nara Prefecture]] | date=April 1, 2015 | accessdate=May 5, 2015 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518074315/http://www.pref.nara.jp/secure/114166/jinkou27-4.xls | archivedate=May 18, 2015 | df= }}</ref> The [[population density]] is 800.61 persons per km², and the total area is 86.37&nbsp;km².{{citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source.|date=May 2015}}
==History== Tenri was briefly the [[capital of Japan]] during the reign of [[Emperor Ninken]].<ref>[[Richard Ponsonby-Fane|Ponsonby-Fane]]. (1915). ''The Imperial Family of Japan,'' p. 15.</ref> The life of the Imperial court was centered at ''Isonokami Hirotaka'' Palace where the emperor lived in 488–498.<ref name="koch">Koch, W. (1904). [https://books.google.com/books?id=LZkCAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA13&dq=Hirotaka++no+miya&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qvShT_XcKMHZgQeghIHkCA&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Hirotaka%20%20no%20miya&f=false ''Japan; Geschichte nach japanischen Quellen und ethnographische Skizzen. Mit einem Stammbaum des Kaisers von Japan,'' p. 13].</ref>
